Their Gallery exhibitions and publications, MA and PhD programs, and research initiatives explore new ways of thinking about decorative arts, design history, and material culture. At Bard Graduate Center, they study the human past through its material traces. They study objects—from those created for obvious aesthetic value to the ordinary things that are part of everyday life. Learning is what Bard Graduate Center is all about. Their accomplished faculty inspire students to strive for excellence, knowing that this will prepare them for the intellectual and professional rigors of careers in academia, in museums, and in the private sector. This high standard is equally the hallmark of the Gallery’s acclaimed exhibitions and related public programs. The Center’s campus comprises a state-of-the-art academic programs building at 38 West 86th Street, the Gallery at 18 West 86th Street, and a residence hall at 410 West 58th Street. Each has been beautifully renovated and designed by the accomplished firm Ennead Architects. Founded by Dr. Susan Weber in 1993, Bard Graduate Center is an academic unit of Bard College through which it is accredited and a member of the Association of Research Institutes in Art History (ARIAH).

Description: An affordable technology to bridge the gap between automation and human workers to provide an efficient way to train restaurant workers.
Headquarters Regions: Washington DC Metro Area, Southern US
Full Description: We are faced with a worker shortage, and restaurants are too busy to provide excellent training due to the lack of team members in the store. Therefore, restaurant owners are turning to artificial intelligence to fill these gaps instead of increasing pay to hire more employees. We see this happening through self-checkout, robocalls, and self-ordering kiosks replacing workers. DoorDash and UberEats have sped up the innovation to find drones to deliver food, and self-driving cars will soon replace humans in the delivery field. We are losing human jobs to computers more and more each day. The problem is that most of these national brands are operated by franchisees and do not have the funds to add full automation to their stores.  Smart Trainer is a hybrid option that uses technology to help provide efficient training in the store and make the job easier. Adding the Smart Trainer in the store will cost less than one team member turnover, allowing operators to make this a no-brainer deal! With a turnover rate of up to 150% per year, you can now hire someone off the street, and using our technology, you can adequately train, cook, and understand the menu mix on the first day to reduce mistakes and serve their product. We know that "practice makes perfect," Our technology will help train new hires through repetition and guidance through consistent voice commands and LED lights.
